 Aieeeeee:
In June 2022, as crypto prices spiraled and Alameda=E2=80=99s lenders were =
calling in their loans, [Caroline] Ellison said she prepared seven =E2=80=
=9Calternative balance sheets=E2=80=9D that would conceal Alameda=E2=80=99s=
 large borrowing from FTX customers, in response to a request for financial=
 information from one of its lenders, Genesis. Alameda had borrowed around =
$10 billion from FTX customers and had loaned around $5 billion to FTX exec=
utives and affiliated entities. =E2=80=9CHe suggested I should prepare some=
 alternative ways of presenting the information and send it to him,=E2=80=
=9D she said. =E2=80=9CI understood him to be directing me to come up with =
ways to conceal things in our balance sheet we both agreed would look bad.=
=E2=80=9D Bankman-Fried told her to send Genesis her Alternative 7 =E2=80=
=94 which didn=E2=80=99t disclose money taken from FTX customers. It cut Al=
ameda=E2=80=99s liabilities from $15 billion to around $10 billion. She tes=
tified that the document was =E2=80=9Cdishonest.=E2=80=9D
If you prepare a balance sheet for a lender and your boss says =E2=80=9Cwhy=
 don=E2=80=99t we present this information in a different way,=E2=80=9D you=
 probably need a lawyer. If you prepare SEVEN BALANCE SHEETS and your boss =
is like =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s go with Alternative 7=E2=80=9D then one of y=
ou is going to prison absolutely forever. Caroline Ellison smartly decided =
it wasn=E2=80=99t going to be her.
Ellison, the chief executive officer of Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s crypto =
trading firm Alameda Research,=C2=A0has been  testifying in Bankman-Fried=
=E2=80=99s criminal trial this week. Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s defense, in th=
e press and to Congress and in his lawyer=E2=80=99s opening statement, has =
been something to the effect of, sure, FTX made some mistakes and lost some=
 customer money, but it was all a series of good-faith accidents; we were j=
ust kids who didn=E2=80=99t know what we were doing. We innocently lost tra=
ck of the money.
And in fact it=C2=A0does=C2=A0seem like FTX couldn=E2=80=99t keep track of =
its money. When it filed for bankruptcy, John Ray (who ran Enron=E2=80=99s =
bankruptcy) came in as CEO and  filed a very grumpy report saying =E2=80=9C=
Never in my career have I seen such a complete failure of corporate control=
s and such a complete absence of trustworthy financial information as occur=
red here=E2=80=9D and complaining that FTX executives =E2=80=9Capproved dis=
bursements by responding with personalized emojis=E2=80=9D on Slack. And wh=
en Bankman-Fried was trying to stave off bankruptcy last November, he  circ=
ulated a spreadsheet=C2=A0listing FTX=E2=80=99s assets and liabilities =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=9Cbalance sheet,=E2=80=9D I and others called it, thou=
gh it was not laid out anything like a traditional balance sheet =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0with an $8 billion entry for =E2=80=9CHidden, poorly internally label=
ed =E2=80=98fiat@=E2=80=99 account.=E2=80=9D The defense is that they forgo=
t that $8 billion was missing, because they were bad at spreadsheets.
Look: The proper number of balance sheets is one.
  [1]
=C2=A0Zero is very bad! At some level I can see =E2=80=9Cwe were careless k=
ids and we never could keep track of how much money we had=E2=80=9D as a pa=
rtial defense to fraud charges. I don=E2=80=99t think it works =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0I think FTX=C2=A0represented=C2=A0that it was being careful with money, =
and if it wasn=E2=80=99t that=E2=80=99s fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it has an =
intuitive appeal.=C2=A0
Seven is much worse! That=E2=80=99s not =E2=80=9Cwe couldn=E2=80=99t keep t=
rack of our money, oops.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cwe had lots of di=
fferent ways to keep track of our money, depending on the audience, and=C2=
=A0we kept coming up with new ways until we got one that looked good.=E2=80=
=9D That=E2=80=99s not =E2=80=9Cwe misplaced our money carelessly=E2=80=9D;=
 that=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cwe misplaced our money and then very carefully cov=
ered it up.=E2=80=9D Zero balance sheets is hapless fraud; seven balance sh=
eets is calculating fraud.
Somehow the story gets worse. For one thing: It=E2=80=99s eight? =E2=80=9CS=
even alternative balance sheets,=E2=80=9D plus the main one.=C2=A0Molly Whi=
te has the spreadsheets; the alts are different tabs in the Google Sheet.=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe =E2=80=98main=E2=80=99=C2=A0spreadsheet was only used in=
ternally, as it accurately reflected Alameda=E2=80=99s terrible financial p=
osition,=E2=80=9D White writes. I mean, not that=C2=A0terrible, in June 202=
2: It shows $21.1 billion of assets, $14.9 billion of liabilities and a net=
 asset value of $6.2 billion. The spreadsheets have quadrants for liquid as=
sets, liquid (i.e. short-term) liabilities, long-term assets and long-term =
liabilities.=C2=A0The liquid=C2=A0liabilities here include=C2=A0$9.9 billio=
n of =E2=80=9Cexchange borrows=E2=80=9D;=C2=A0the long-term assets include =
$4.6 billion of =E2=80=9Crelated party loans.=E2=80=9D
Alternative 7, the one they sent to Genesis, deletes the related party loan=
s entirely, because they look bad, reducing Alameda=E2=80=99s assets from $=
21.1 billion to $16.5 billion. It keeps the net asset value the same, at $6=
.2 billion, and solves for this by reducing the liabilities to $10.3 billio=
n. It deletes the entry for =E2=80=9Cexchange borrows,=E2=80=9D reducing Al=
ameda=E2=80=99s displayed short-term borrowing from $10.7 billion (=E2=80=
=9Cexchange borrows=E2=80=9D plus =E2=80=9COT loans,=E2=80=9D i.e. open ter=
m loans) to $1.8 billion (just the OT loans). It combines the $9.9 billion =
of exchange borrowing with $2.9 billion of longer-term loans to get, uh, we=
ll, my math would say that=E2=80=99s $12.8 billion of loans, but Alternativ=
e 7 reports $8.2 billion of loans. The difference is $4.6 billion, which is=
 exactly what they lopped off the assets by deleting the related party loan=
s.
The result is a balance sheet that is less levered (liabilities of 63% of a=
ssets instead of 71%) and more liquid (liquid assets of 395% of =E2=80=9Cli=
quid liabilities,=E2=80=9D instead of just 61%).
Which seems like fraud. Possibly more offensive is the fact that they seem =
to have=C2=A0started with a net asset value of $6.2 billion and USED THE EN=
TRY FOR =E2=80=9CLOANS=E2=80=9D AS A PLUG.=C2=A0I am not an accountant or a=
nything but I will say that the=C2=A0good=C2=A0way to do a balance sheet is=
:
=09Add up your assets.=09Add up your liabilities.=09Subtract the liabilitie=
s from the assets to get your net asset value.

And a bad way would be:
=09Start with the net asset value you want.=09Add up your assets.=09Delete =
the=C2=A0embarrassing ones.=09Subtract the assets you have left=C2=A0from y=
our net asset value to get your liabilities.=09Just make up some numbers fo=
r individual liabilities to get the right total.

My conclusion from this is that FTX was in fact extremely bad at accounting=
, but not in a charming innocent way.

