I   wrote yesterday that Sculptor Capital Management Inc.=E2=80=99s board s=
eemed to be softening on Boaz Weinstein=E2=80=99s offer to buy it, but  tha=
t=E2=80=99s just what they wanted me to think:

Rithm Capital Corp. (NYSE: RITM) (=E2=80=9CRithm=E2=80=9D) and Sculptor Cap=
ital Management Inc. (NYSE: SCU) (=E2=80=9CSculptor=E2=80=9D) today announc=
ed that they have amended the terms of their previously announced definitiv=
e merger agreement (the =E2=80=9CAmended Agreement=E2=80=9D), pursuant to w=
hich Rithm will acquire Sculptor. Under the Amended Agreement, which has be=
en unanimously approved by the boards of directors of both companies, Sculp=
tor Class A stockholders will receive $12.00 per share, representing an inc=
rease of 7.62% over Rithm=E2=80=99s previously agreed price of $11.15 per C=
lass A share announced on July 24, 2023, and an aggregate transaction value=
 of approximately $676 million. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CThroughout this process, the Special Committee has been solely foc=
used on consummating a transaction that maximizes value and certainty of cl=
osing for Sculptor stockholders. We are pleased to have been able to delive=
r a price increase and believe this transaction is in the best interest of =
Sculptor=E2=80=99s stockholders,=E2=80=9D said Marcy Engel, Chairperson of =
Sculptor=E2=80=99s Board of Directors.

I suppose the story here might be:
=09Sculptor did not want to take Weinstein=E2=80=99s offer of $12.76 or so,=
 but couldn=E2=80=99t really excuse sticking with Rithm=E2=80=99s $11.15, s=
o it=C2=A0was trying to get Rithm to raise its price.=09Rithm said no, larg=
ely because Sculptor=E2=80=99s estranged founder, Dan Och, refused to suppo=
rt the Rithm deal (because he preferred Weinstein).=09So Sculptor put out a=
  revised proxy statement last week saying that it was =E2=80=9Cpreparing r=
evised draft definitive transaction documents to send to [Weinstein=E2=80=
=99s]=C2=A0Consortium=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccontinuing to evaluate [Weinste=
in=E2=80=99s]=C2=A0September 30 Proposal,=E2=80=9D suggesting that it reall=
y might ditch Rithm for Weinstein.=09Rithm was like fine, fine, $12.

Sculptor put out  another revised proxy statement this morning with the det=
ails of the timeline. It suggests that the board never really softened that=
 much on Weinstein: It gave him a deadline of this Monday to sign a merger =
agreement, without much time to do due diligence, and continues to fret tha=
t Weinstein=E2=80=99s consortium of famous rich hedge fund managers might n=
ot have enough money to close the deal. Sculptor engaged=C2=A0a little=C2=
=A0more with Weinstein than it had previously, but not much.
Instead, Sculptor took $12 from Rithm instead of trying to get $13 from Wei=
nstein. And the new Rithm deal is  a lot more locked up than the old one. F=
or one thing, Sculptor raised the breakup fee that it will have to pay Rith=
m if it takes another deal, from $16.6 million to $20.3 million.
For another thing, the original deal  required two shareholder votes:
=09A majority of all shares had to vote in favor of the deal, and=09A major=
ity of all shares=C2=A0not=C2=A0held by Sculptor partners=C2=A0had to vote =
in favor of the deals. By =E2=80=9CSculptor partners=E2=80=9D I mean holder=
s of units in Sculptor=E2=80=99s operating partnerships, which means basica=
lly its current and former executives. In particular, Sculptor=E2=80=99s cu=
rrent executives, including chief executive officer Jimmy Levin,  own about=
 26.7%=C2=A0of the voting power and have  agreed to vote for the deal. Its =
former executives also own shares, though, and Och and Robert Shafir, forme=
r executives who have come out against the Rithm deal, own about 15.8% betw=
een them. The second vote would exclude all of their votes and basically re=
quire a majority of unaffiliated public shareholders to approve the deal.

The revised deal  requires only the first vote: The requirement to get a vo=
te of unaffiliated public shareholders is gone. Even if Rithm can=E2=80=99t=
 get a majority of outside shareholders to approve the deal (because they p=
refer $13 to $12, and, unlike the board, think that Weinstein would be able=
 to sign and close a deal), it can still win the vote, because it has about=
 26% of the vote already locked up from executives who prefer a Rithm deal =
to a Weinstein one.
  [2]

For another thing, in 2020, as part of a lending deal with Delaware Life In=
surance Company, Sculptor issued warrants to buy about 4.3 million shares o=
f its stock at $7.95 per share. As part of the new merger agreement, Rithm =
will buy those warrants from Delaware Life; if it exercises them it will ha=
ve roughly=C2=A07% of the voting power of Sculptor, in addition to the 26% =
that is already locked up. It=E2=80=99s not a majority, but it makes it har=
der for shareholders to vote down the deal.
It is an odd result. Weinstein has offered to pay $13 per share for Sculpto=
r, and Sculptor=E2=80=99s board has gone back and agreed to take $12 per sh=
are from Rithm, while also making it much harder for shareholders to say no=
 to that lower price. All to take a deal that is, on its face,=C2=A0worse=
=C2=A0than Weinstein=E2=80=99s deal.
I don=E2=80=99t know! The board has its reasons: It worries that, if it too=
k Weinstein=E2=80=99s deal, its employees and clients would all flee, and t=
hen Weinstein wouldn=E2=80=99t have to close. In the latest proxy, it expla=
ins that it asked Weinstein to assume all of that risk, and he said no:

The Special Committee[=E2=80=99s proposed merger agreement]=C2=A0(1) remove=
d all client revenue run-rate consent conditions in their entirety, and pla=
ced the risk of business deterioration due to the announcement of the trans=
action on the Consortium, and (2) included provisions requiring the Consort=
ium to assume certain closing risks that arose solely as a result of the Co=
nsortium, including, for example, certain adverse client and employee react=
ions based on a transaction with the Consortium members (the =E2=80=9CConso=
rtium-Specific Transaction Risks=E2=80=9D). =E2=80=A6
The Consortium conveyed that it was only prepared to execute the draft of t=
he merger agreement provided by the Consortium with the October 10 Response=
, which draft had (1) re-inserted client run rate consent conditions of 70%=
 for the Real Estate business line and 80% for the Company=E2=80=99s CLO bu=
siness line, and (2) rejected the requirement that the Consortium assume th=
e Consortium-Specific Transaction Risks.

And I suppose if you think this is a serious risk, then a fairly certain $1=
2 is better than a risky $13. And if you think you know this better than yo=
ur shareholders do, then you might take the decision out of their hands.
But man are there gonna be lawsuits.
What has fascinated me about this deal from the beginning is that there are=
   not a lot of hostile takeovers of hedge funds. In principle, you could i=
magine this sort of situation playing out in any merger:
=09The board has one offer from a boring stable acquirer who will pay $12 p=
er share and=C2=A0will keep all of the employees around.=C2=A0=09The board =
has another offer from a bitter rival who will pay $13 per share but has ba=
d blood with all of the employees.=09The board has fiduciary duties to the =
shareholders and=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0really consider its fondness for t=
he employees in choosing between these bids. It has to do what is best for =
shareholders.
  [3]

=09But! The board can say, well, if we take our bitter rival=E2=80=99s $13 =
bid, all of our employees will quit the day after we sign the agreement. Th=
en we=E2=80=99ll lose all of our customers. The business will collapse. And=
 then our bitter rival=C2=A0will be able to get out of the deal. It will cl=
aim a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D; it will say that the colla=
pse of the business gives it a right to get out of the deal.
  [4]
=C2=A0And then=C2=A0our shareholders=C2=A0will be left with nothing. Our bi=
tter rival won=E2=80=99t close, the $12 bidder will be gone, we=E2=80=99ll =
have no deal and no business.=09Meanwhile, if we take the boring stable acq=
uirer=E2=80=99s $12 bid, that deal will close and our shareholders will get=
 their $12.=09So better,=C2=A0for shareholders, to take the deal with the l=
ower price that will keep all the employees, rather than to take the deal w=
ith the higher price that won=E2=80=99t.=09For form=E2=80=99s sake, you can=
 go back to the bitter rival and say =E2=80=9Cokay we=E2=80=99ll take your =
$13, but you have to sign a merger agreement that acknowledges that all the=
 employees will quit, all the customers=C2=A0will be gone, revenue will go =
to zero by closing, and you will nonetheless have to=C2=A0buy the smoking c=
rater of a company for $13 per share.=E2=80=9D And=C2=A0when you put it lik=
e that, the rival will say no.
  [5]

=09So you=E2=80=99ll take the $12.

That is effectively what is happening here, but I don=E2=80=99t think I=E2=
=80=99ve ever seen it before. In ordinary businesses, a change in ownership=
 tends not to lead to an immediate collapse in the business, particularly n=
ot between signing and closing of a deal. If a private equity firm buys a r=
etailer, a lot of store employees are going to say =E2=80=9Cuh oh=E2=80=9D =
and maybe start looking for another job. And maybe, after the deal closes, =
the buyer will shut down a lot of stores and cut staffing and lower morale,=
 making the shopping experience worse, driving away customers and ultimatel=
y bankrupting the business. But that won=E2=80=99t all happen=C2=A0before c=
losing. There are too many employees, and they are too far removed from the=
 ownership. The company has inertia; a change in ownership might lead to a =
deterioration in the business, but not=C2=A0instantly.=C2=A0
Whereas a hedge fund is an unusually pure case of a business where the asse=
ts walk out the door each night, and where personality fit matters a lot. I=
f you are in Jimmy Levin=E2=80=99s pirate crew, and Boaz Weinstein=E2=80=99=
s pirate ship captures your ship, your first instinct might not be to=C2=A0=
join his crew. Weinstein wants to buy Sculptor, but =E2=80=9Cbuy Sculptor=
=E2=80=9D doesn=E2=80=99t just mean acquiring the corporate entity. It mean=
s=C2=A0acquiring=C2=A0Sculptor=E2=80=99s people and clients, and the people=
 and clients have a lot of agency here. There is some risk that Weinstein m=
ight sign a deal to buy Sculptor and end up with only an empty shell, not t=
he people and clients.=C2=A0
By the way, there is one recent deal that looks a little bit like this.=C2=
=A0Last year, you might remember, Elon Musk signed a deal to buy Twitter In=
c., after saying very mean things about Twitter and its employees in public=
. A lot of Twitter employees were unhappy when the deal was signed; their n=
ew ownership was very salient and very different, and some of them reacted =
by looking for new jobs more or less instantly, well before the deal closed=
.
And they were correct to worry; since closing, Musk has laid off or driven =
out a majority of employees and dramatically changed the whole vibe of the =
company and its product. And that does seem to have been bad for business, =
and Twitter (now called X) is worth dramatically less than Musk paid for it=
.=C2=A0
And in fact Musk=C2=A0did=C2=A0try to get out of the deal after signing it.=
 His reasons were   mostly nonsense, and it would be a stretch to say =E2=
=80=9Che wanted to get out of his deal to buy Twitter because the announcem=
ent of the deal caused employees and advertisers to flee.=E2=80=9D But ther=
e=E2=80=99s a little something to that: When Musk tried to terminate the de=
al,   one reason that he gave was that =E2=80=9Cthree executives have resig=
ned from Twitter since the Merger Agreement was signed,=E2=80=9D which he a=
rgued was a violation of Twitter=E2=80=99s promise to operate in the ordina=
ry course of business between signing and closing. This was, to be fair, ab=
surd, but his lawyers did say it, and he might even have thought it. His de=
al to buy Twitter did drive down the value of Twitter, and he did then try =
to get out of the deal; it is not crazy to think the two things might be re=
