       =20
  [1] Oh obviously that is oversimplified. Your tax books and your financia=
l-reporting books won=E2=80=99t line up in every respect, and the accounts =
you use to run your business will probably require some adjusting for finan=
cial reporting purposes. Still, if you=E2=80=99ve got one set of books with=
 $10 billion of customer borrowing and $5 billion of loans to insiders, and=
 another set without it, that=E2=80=99s not a nuanced adjustment to reflect=
 the oddities of generally accepted accounting principles.


  [2] The reason for this is that the original deal offered partnership uni=
tholders (including Och) the right to keep their partnership interests inst=
ead of being cashed out and   paying taxes. Thus the partnership unitholder=
s were offered a different deal from the public shareholders, so there need=
ed to be a separate vote. The new deal cashes everyone out, so there=E2=80=
=99s no separate vote.=20


  [3] This is mainly true where the board is choosing between all-cash deal=
s. In stock deals, the board might reasonably consider which acquirer will =
run the business better going forward, since its shareholders will particip=
ate. In a cash deal the shareholders don=E2=80=99t care about the business =
going forward, they just want to make sure they get their cash.


  [4] It is customary for MAE clauses to exclude material adverse effects *=
caused* by the signing of the deal, or by the acquirer, but it=E2=80=99s a =
little fuzzy to prove that. If you=E2=80=99re a target board and you are su=
re that the deal announcement will destroy the business, relying on that st=
andard MAE language is risky.


  [5] Because the proper allocation of this risk is not really entirely to =
either the acquirer or the target. The proper allocation of the risk is, li=
ke, =E2=80=9Cthe acquirer and the target should work together to keep the e=
mployees and the customers.=E2=80=9D If the risk is entirely on one of them=
, then the other has no incentive to help. In Sculptor, if there are no cli=
ent consent or material-adverse-effect conditions, then the employees could=
 just badmouth Weinstein, take another job and take clients with them; they=
 need to have some incentive to keep the company going until closing.


  [6] A third, intermediate use would be: Asset managers own stocks in diff=
erent countries and want to hedge their currency risk.


  [7] Perhaps more to the point, it was not *predictable* that the stock wo=
uld drop on this news =E2=80=94 this news is plausibly immaterial, and argu=
ably *good*. Meme stocks, man.


