bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> that=E2=80=99s just what the=
y wanted me to think</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rithm Capital Corp. (NYSE: RITM) (=E2=80=9CRit=
hm=E2=80=9D) and Sculptor Capital Management Inc. (NYSE: SCU) (=E2=80=9CScu=
lptor=E2=80=9D) today announced that they have amended the terms of their p=
reviously announced definitive merger agreement (the =E2=80=9CAmended Agree=
ment=E2=80=9D), pursuant to which Rithm will acquire Sculptor. Under the Am=
ended Agreement, which has been unanimously approved by the boards of direc=
tors of both companies, Sculptor Class A stockholders will receive $12.00 p=
er share, representing an increase of 7.62% over Rithm=E2=80=99s previously=
 agreed price of $11.15 per Class A share announced on July 24, 2023, and a=
n aggregate transaction value of approximately $676 million. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThroughout this process, the Special =
Committee has been solely focused on consummating a transaction that maximi=
zes value and certainty of closing for Sculptor stockholders. We are please=
d to have been able to deliver a price increase and believe this transactio=
n is in the best interest of Sculptor=E2=80=99s stockholders,=E2=80=9D said=
 Marcy Engel, Chairperson of Sculptor=E2=80=99s Board of Directors.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose the story here might be:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sculptor did not want to take Weinstei=
n=E2=80=99s offer of $12.76 or so, but couldn=E2=80=99t really excuse stick=
ing with Rithm=E2=80=99s $11.15, so it=C2=A0was trying to get Rithm to rais=
e its price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Rithm said no, largel=
y because Sculptor=E2=80=99s estranged founder, Dan Och, refused to support=
 the Rithm deal (because he preferred Weinstein).</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">So Sculptor put out a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/33007895.258422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9=
lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE0MDM2MTIzMDQ3MTkwL255MjAwMDk5Mzl4MTFfcHJlcj=
E0YS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB39ca7790" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> revised proxy stateme=
nt</a> last week saying that it was =E2=80=9Cpreparing revised draft defini=
tive transaction documents to send to [Weinstein=E2=80=99s]=C2=A0Consortium=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccontinuing to evaluate [Weinstein=E2=80=99s]=C2=A0Se=
ptember 30 Proposal,=E2=80=9D suggesting that it really might ditch Rithm f=
or Weinstein.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Rithm was like fine,=
 fine, $12.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sculptor put out <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/33007895.258422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmN=
oaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE0MDM2MTIzMDQ3OTY4L255MjAwMDk5Mzl4MT=
JfZGVmbTE0YS5odG0jdEJN/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa6f98e34" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> another =
revised proxy statement</a> this morning with the details of the timeline. =
It suggests that the board never really softened that much on Weinstein: It=
 gave him a deadline of this Monday to sign a merger agreement, without muc=
h time to do due diligence, and continues to fret that Weinstein=E2=80=99s =
consortium of famous rich hedge fund managers might not have enough money t=
o close the deal. Sculptor engaged=C2=A0<em>a little=C2=A0</em>more with We=
instein than it had previously, but not much.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, Sculptor took $12 from Rithm instead =
of trying to get $13 from Weinstein. And the new Rithm deal is <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33007895.258422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTQwMzI1Ni8wMDAxMTQwMzYxM=
jMwNDc5NjEvbnkyMDAwOTkzOXgxNF84ay5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa8402264" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> a lot more locked up</a> than the old one. For one thing, Sculptor =
raised the breakup fee that it will have to pay Rithm if it takes another d=
eal, from $16.6 million to $20.3 million.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For another thing, the original deal <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33007895.258422/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE0MDM2MTIzMDQ3=
MTkwL255MjAwMDk5Mzl4MTFfcHJlcjE0YS5odG0jdFZORQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe72=
e09d8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;"> required two shareholder votes</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A majority of all shares had to vote =
in favor of the deal, and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A majori=
ty of all shares=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>held by Sculptor partners=C2=A0had =
to vote in favor of the deals. By =E2=80=9CSculptor partners=E2=80=9D I mea=
n holders of units in Sculptor=E2=80=99s operating partnerships, which mean=
s basically its current and former executives. In particular, Sculptor=E2=
=80=99s current executives, including chief executive officer Jimmy Levin, =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33007895.258422/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE0MDM2M=
TIzMDQ3OTY4L255MjAwMDk5Mzl4MTJfZGVmbTE0YS5odG0jdFNPQw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB80e3f7c4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> own about</a> 26.7%=C2=A0of the voting power and hav=
e <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33007895.258422/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE0MDM=
2MTIzMDQ3OTY4L255MjAwMDk5Mzl4MTJfZGVmbTE0YS5odG0jdFZB/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB0e496446" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> agreed to vote</a> for the deal. Its former executiv=
es also own shares, though, and Och and Robert Shafir, former executives wh=
o have come out against the Rithm deal, own about 15.8% between them. The s=
econd vote would exclude all of their votes and basically require a majorit=
y of unaffiliated public shareholders to approve the deal.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The revised deal <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/33007895.258422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmN=
oaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE0MDM2MTIzMDQ3OTY4L255MjAwMDk5Mzl4MT=
JfZGVmbTE0YS5odG0jdFZORQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8127395a" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> requir=
es only the first vote</a>: The requirement to get a vote of unaffiliated p=
ublic shareholders is gone. Even if Rithm can=E2=80=99t get a majority of o=
utside shareholders to approve the deal (because they prefer $13 to $12, an=
d, unlike the board, think that Weinstein would be able to sign and close a=
 deal), it can still win the vote, because it has about 26% of the vote alr=
eady locked up from executives who prefer a Rithm deal to a Weinstein one.<=
a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transp=
arent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For another thing, in 2020, as part of a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33007895.258422/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIwMj=
U0NzE1L2Q5MDU4NjFkZXgxMDEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6a7a0f19" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
lending deal with</a> Delaware Life Insurance Company, Sculptor issued warr=
ants to buy about 4.3 million shares of its stock at $7.95 per share. As pa=
rt of the new merger agreement, Rithm will buy those warrants from Delaware=
 Life; if it exercises them it will have roughly=C2=A07% of the voting powe=
r of Sculptor, in addition to the 26% that is already locked up. It=E2=80=
=99s not a majority, but it makes it harder for shareholders to vote down t=
he deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is an odd result. Weinstein has offered to =
pay $13 per share for Sculptor, and Sculptor=E2=80=99s board has gone back =
and agreed to take $12 per share from Rithm, while also making it much hard=
er for shareholders to say no to that lower price. All to take a deal that =
is, on its face,=C2=A0<em>worse=C2=A0</em>than Weinstein=E2=80=99s deal.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know! The board has its reason=
s: It worries that, if it took Weinstein=E2=80=99s deal, its employees and =
clients would all flee, and then Weinstein wouldn=E2=80=99t have to close. =
In the latest proxy, it explains that it asked Weinstein to assume all of t=
hat risk, and he said no:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Special Committee[=E2=80=99s proposed merg=
er agreement]=C2=A0(1) removed all client revenue run-rate consent conditio=
ns in their entirety, and placed the risk of business deterioration due to =
the announcement of the transaction on the Consortium, and (2) included pro=
visions requiring the Consortium to assume certain closing risks that arose=
 solely as a result of the Consortium, including, for example, certain adve=
rse client and employee reactions based on a transaction with the Consortiu=
m members (the =E2=80=9CConsortium-Specific Transaction Risks=E2=80=9D). =
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Consortium conveyed that it was only prepa=
red to execute the draft of the merger agreement provided by the Consortium=
 with the October 10 Response, which draft had (1) re-inserted client run r=
ate consent conditions of 70% for the Real Estate business line and 80% for=
 the Company=E2=80=99s CLO business line, and (2) rejected the requirement =
that the Consortium assume the Consortium-Specific Transaction Risks.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And I suppose if you think this is a serious r=
isk, then a fairly certain $12 is better than a risky $13. And if you think=
 you know this better than your shareholders do, then you might take the de=
cision out of their hands.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But man are there gonna be lawsuits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What has fascinated me about this deal from th=
e beginning is that there are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/33007895.258422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMjEvZXZlcnlvbmUtd2FudHMtYS1waWVjZS1vZi1zY3VscHRvcj9jbX=
BpZD1CQkQxMDEyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c=
2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMTImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBa8cbe714" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">  not a lot of hostile takeovers of hedge fu=
nds</a>. In principle, you could imagine this sort of situation playing out=
 in any merger:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The board has one offer from a boring=
 stable acquirer who will pay $12 per share and=C2=A0will keep all of the e=
mployees around.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The board h=
as another offer from a bitter rival who will pay $13 per share but has bad=
 blood with all of the employees.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
The board has fiduciary duties to the shareholders and=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0</em>really consider its fondness for the employees in choosing b=
etween these bids. It has to do what is best for shareholders.<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But! The board can say, well, if =
we take our bitter rival=E2=80=99s $13 bid, all of our employees will quit =
the day after we sign the agreement. Then we=E2=80=99ll lose all of our cus=
tomers. The business will collapse. And then our bitter rival=C2=A0<em>will=
 be able to get out of the deal</em>. It will claim a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adv=
erse effect=E2=80=9D; it will say that the collapse of the business gives i=
t a right to get out of the deal.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
>
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And then=C2=A0<em>our shareholders=C2=A0</em>will be left with no=
thing. Our bitter rival won=E2=80=99t close, the $12 bidder will be gone, w=
e=E2=80=99ll have no deal and no business.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">Meanwhile, if we take the boring stable acquirer=E2=80=99s $12 bid=
, that deal will close and our shareholders will get their $12.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So better,=C2=A0<em>for shareholders</em>, to=
 take the deal with the lower price that will keep all the employees, rathe=
r than to take the deal with the higher price that won=E2=80=99t.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">For form=E2=80=99s sake, you can go back to=
 the bitter rival and say =E2=80=9Cokay we=E2=80=99ll take your $13, but yo=
u have to sign a merger agreement that acknowledges that all the employees =
will quit, all the customers=C2=A0will be gone, revenue will go to zero by =
closing, and you will nonetheless have to=C2=A0buy the smoking crater of a =
company for $13 per share.=E2=80=9D And=C2=A0<em>when you put it like that<=
/em>, the rival will say no.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So you=E2=80=99ll take the $12.</=
li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is effectively what is happening here, bu=
t I don=E2=80=99t think I=E2=80=99ve ever seen it before. In ordinary busin=
esses, a change in ownership tends not to lead to an immediate collapse in =
the business, particularly not between signing and closing of a deal. If a =
private equity firm buys a retailer, a lot of store employees are going to =
say =E2=80=9Cuh oh=E2=80=9D and maybe start looking for another job. And ma=
ybe, after the deal closes, the buyer will shut down a lot of stores and cu=
t staffing and lower morale, making the shopping experience worse, driving =
away customers and ultimately bankrupting the business. But that won=E2=80=
=99t all happen=C2=A0<em>before closing.</em> There are too many employees,=
 and they are too far removed from the ownership. The company has inertia; =
a change in ownership might lead to a deterioration in the business, but no=
t=C2=A0<em>instantly</em>.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Whereas a hedge fund is an unusually pure case=
 of a business where the assets walk out the door each night, and where per=
sonality fit matters a lot. If you are in Jimmy Levin=E2=80=99s pirate crew=
, and Boaz Weinstein=E2=80=99s pirate ship captures your ship, your first i=
nstinct might not be to=C2=A0join his crew. Weinstein wants to buy Sculptor=
, but =E2=80=9Cbuy Sculptor=E2=80=9D doesn=E2=80=99t just mean acquiring th=
e corporate entity. It means=C2=A0acquiring=C2=A0Sculptor=E2=80=99s people =
and clients, and the people and clients have a lot of agency here. There is=
 some risk that Weinstein might sign a deal to buy Sculptor and end up with=
 only an empty shell, not the people and clients.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way, there is <em>one</em> recent deal =
that looks a <em>little</em> bit like this.=C2=A0Last year, you might remem=
ber, Elon Musk signed a deal to buy Twitter Inc., after saying very mean th=
ings about Twitter and its employees in public. A lot of Twitter employees =
were unhappy when the deal was signed; their new ownership was very salient=
 and very different, and some of them reacted by looking for new jobs more =
or less instantly, well before the deal closed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And they were correct to worry; since closing,=
 Musk has laid off or driven out a majority of employees and dramatically c=
hanged the whole vibe of the company and its product. And that does seem to=
 have been bad for business, and Twitter (now called X) is worth dramatical=
ly less than Musk paid for it.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in fact Musk=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>try to=
 get out of the deal after signing it. His reasons were <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33007895.258422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMTgvZWxvbi13YW50cy10by1maWdo=
dC10aGUtYm90cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDEyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV=
0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMTImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3=
R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBee909664" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  mostly nonsense</a>, a=
nd it would be a stretch to say =E2=80=9Che wanted to get out of his deal t=
o buy Twitter because the announcement of the deal caused employees and adv=
ertisers to flee.=E2=80=9D But there=E2=80=99s a little something to that: =
When Musk tried to terminate the deal, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/33007895.258422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMDkvZWxvbi1zLW91dD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDEyMjNfTU9OR=
VlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0y=
MzEwMTImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0983bb1c" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">  one reason that he gave</a> was that =E2=80=9Cthree executives ha=
ve resigned from Twitter since the Merger Agreement was signed,=E2=80=9D wh=
ich he argued was a violation of Twitter=E2=80=99s promise to operate in th=
e ordinary course of business between signing and closing. This was, to be =
fair, absurd, but his lawyers did say it, and he might even have thought it=
. His deal to buy Twitter did drive down the value of Twitter, and he did t=
hen try to get out of the deal; it is not crazy to think the two things mig=
ht be related.</p>
