<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are two classic uses for foreign exchange=
 derivatives<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Real companies in the real economy ma=
ke and=C2=A0sell stuff in different countries, have revenues and expenses i=
n different currencies, and want to hedge their currency risk.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Hedge funds want to make macro bets on countri=
es by trading those countries=E2=80=99 currencies.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a bank FX desk, which clients would=
 you prefer? The advantages of hedge-fund clients include (1) they trade a =
lot, so you have lots of opportunities to make money and (2) if you cover t=
hem well, you might get to leave your job at the bank and take a job at the=
 hedge fund, which probably pays better.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The advantages of corporate clients include:</=
p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They don=E2=80=99t trade=C2=A0<em>oppo=
rtunistically</em>. They have foreign revenue each quarter and have to hedg=
e it. They=E2=80=99re not buying euro options because they think the euro i=
s going up. This means both that they are a more steady stream of business =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0they trade every quarter instead of trading a lot when the m=
arket is hot and nothing when it=E2=80=99s slow =E2=80=94=C2=A0and also tha=
t they are not a huge source of adverse selection. If a hedge fund comes to=
 you looking to buy euros, they probably think the euro is going up, and th=
ere=E2=80=99s a good chance they=E2=80=99re right, so you=E2=80=99ll probab=
ly lose money on the trade. If a corporate client comes to you=C2=A0looking=
 to buy euros, there=E2=80=99s a decent chance that=E2=80=99s random noise =
and you=E2=80=99ll make money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The=
y=E2=80=99re probably nicer? This is not always and everywhere true, but =
=E2=80=9Ccorporate treasurer=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Chedge fund execution tra=
der=E2=80=9D are different jobs that attract different personality types an=
d have different sorts of performance evaluation. If you=E2=80=99re selling=
 derivatives to=C2=A0 corporate treasurers, you can work to build=C2=A0rela=
tionships, taking them out to dinner and sending them research and introduc=
ing them to other product specialists at your bank. And then they will trad=
e with you at the prices you propose, and have a friendly chat while doing =
it. If you=E2=80=99re selling derivatives to hedge fund traders they are ge=
tting prices from six other banks and will take the cheapest, while yelling=
=C2=A0at you.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A more abstract advantage of corporate clients=
 is, like, what is the point of all of this? If you sell FX derivatives to =
corporate clients, you can tell your parents =E2=80=9Cwhat I do is reduce r=
isk so that companies call sell their products all over the world.=E2=80=9D=
 Your work has an effect on the real economy. If you sell FX derivatives to=
 hedge funds, the story is kind of =E2=80=9Cwell there=E2=80=99s this casin=
o and I=E2=80=99m the dealer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Alice Atkins and Jen=
nifer Surane have a story about how <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/33007895.258422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMTIvY29ycG9yYXRlLWdpYW50cy1hcmUtdGhlLW5ldy1oZWRnZS1m=
dW5kcy1vZi10aGUtZ2xvYmFsLWZ4LW1hcmtldD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDEyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ=
1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMTImdX=
RtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8f76049f" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  FX is increasingly dominated by corporate clients</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These days, Wall Street=E2=80=99s biggest bank=
s are increasingly asking their currency traders to cater to the largest co=
mpanies on the planet in their hunt for more stable, recurring fees. =E2=80=
=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Companies have become the bread and butter of =
currency divisions, bringing not just consistent business but fatter margin=
s. Revenue in corporate currency business at the world=E2=80=99s five bigge=
st banks has jumped about 30% in the past five years, according to data fir=
m Vali Analytics. For the top 50 banks, it now accounts on average for more=
 than half of all currency revenue. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The change is partly related to new regulation=
s that forced lenders to cut back on their currency trading offerings for t=
he world=E2=80=99s largest asset managers in the aftermath of the global fi=
nancial crisis.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other driving force has been the decline i=
n currency volatility. That crucial juice for the market waned during the p=
eriod of ultra-low interest rates and quantitative easing, and many investo=
rs just quit the market. The number of FX-focused hedge funds has dwindled =
82% from its all-time high in 2007. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, it=E2=80=99s not only the consistency o=
f the orders, regardless of market backdrop, that makes growing corporate c=
lient share attractive. Banks can typically reap a higher margin too.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since corporate clients often rely on their ba=
nk for multiple services like borrowing, debt issuance or advisory, the rel=
ative benefit of shopping around for cheaper FX pricing is smaller. On top =
of that, firms often have treasury policies that only permit the use of cer=
tain banks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not always about who has=
 the cheapest price,=E2=80=9D said Naresh Aggarwal, an associate director a=
t the Association of Corporate Treasurers. Instead, it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cw=
ho=E2=80=99s going to give me the best overall service.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a bank salesperson, you want to be =
selling to the people who want good service, not the people who want a chea=
p price.</p>
